  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "DXY in an expansion phase on the weekly/daily chart. Analyst marks the initial weekly range from high to low to derive equilibrium, then drops to the daily to identify discount PD arrays for long entries as price creates successive nested ranges while trending higher.",
  "key_observation": "As DXY expanded higher, each new swing high/low created a fresh range whose equilibrium had to be re-marked. Price repeatedly reached into discount PD arrays (fair value gap, then order block) before expanding higher, illustrating how ranges nest within ranges during a trend.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the weekly DXY chart, mark the move from the recent high down to the low to establish the first equilibrium range.",
    "Step 2: Drop down to the daily chart and, given long bias, look for a PD array in the discount half of the range.",
    "Step 3: Identify a fair value gap sitting in discount and wait for price to reach into it; price taps the discount FVG and moves higher.",
    "Step 4: Once price expands, redraw a new range from the new high to the new low and locate the new equilibrium.",
    "Step 5: Observe a reversal model: lower-timeframe low swept, structure broken up, and a new displacement range marked from high to low.",
    "Step 6: In the new range's discount, identify an order block as the next PD array; price reaches in, respects the order block's opening price, and expands higher.",
    "Step 7: Mark out the newest range from the new high to new low and continue tracking premium/discount for subsequent entries."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "In a trending market, ranges nest within ranges. Continuously re-mark equilibrium as each new swing forms, and only seek longs from discount PD arrays (FVGs, order blocks) within the most recent range to stay aligned with the expansion.",
